{"title_page": "Almonte, Ontario", "text_new": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Almonte\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Community <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = File:Almonte Ontario Canada.jpeg\n|imagesize              = 300px\n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Ontario<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Ontario\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 170\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Canada}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Ontario}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Lanark County, Ontario|Lanark]]\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =     \n|leader_name            = \n|leader_title1          =\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = 4.41\n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_water_percent       = \n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 4,752\n|population_density_km2         = 1077.4 \n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|45.22629|-76.19452|region:CA-ON_type:city(4649)|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n| postal_code_type      = Postal Code\n| postal_code           = K0A 1A0 & K0A 4A0\n|area_code              = [[Area code 613|613]]\n|blank_name             = [[Telephone exchange|256]]\n|blank_info             =  \n|footnotes              =  \n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n'''Almonte''' (pronounced \"AL-mont\" as opposed to the original Spanish pronunciation of \"al-MON-tay\")  is a former mill town located in [[Lanark County, Ontario|Lanark County]], in the eastern portion of Ontario, Canada. Formerly a separate municipality, Almonte is now a ward of the town of [[Mississippi Mills, Ontario|Mississippi Mills]], which was created on January 1, 1998, by the merging of Almonte with Ramsay and Pakenham townships.<ref>County of Lanark website  [http://www.county.lanark.on.ca/Page283.aspx ''Lanark County: Local Municipalities''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828095815/http://www.county.lanark.on.ca/Page283.aspx |date=2010-08-28 }}, last retrieved February 14, 2010</ref> Almonte is located {{convert|46|km|mi|0}} south-west of downtown [[Ottawa]]. Its population as of 2013 is about 5,000.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mississippi Mills Waterfalls.jpeg|thumb|right|Mississippi Mills Waterfalls]]\n\n===First settlers===\nAlmonte's first European-bred settler was David Shepherd, who in 1818 was given {{convert|200|acre|km2}} by the Crown to build and operate a [[Mill (grinding)|mill]].  The site became known as Shepherd's Falls.  That name was never official, however, and Shepherd sold his [[patent]] after his mill burned down.  The buyer of the patent, [[Daniel Shipman]], rebuilt the mill and the settlement became known as Shipman's Mills by about 1821.<ref>Wheatley, Gerry. [http://almonte.clal.ca/articles/almonte_early_history.htm \"David Shepherd was Almonte's first settler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223223039/http://almonte.clal.ca/articles/almonte_early_history.htm |date=2008-12-23 }}, ''The Almonte Gazette'', Almonte,  February 26, 1992</ref>\n\nThe majority of Shipman's Mills' early settlers were [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and later [[Irish people|Irish]].   A textile town almost from the start, by 1850 it was the home of seven busy woolen mills of Messrs B & W Rosamond. It was one of the leading centres in Ontario for the manufacture of woollen cloth. \nThe construction of a railway line to Brockville stimulated the economic growth of Almonte.\n\nIn 1869, Almonte was a village with a population of 2000 situated on the Mississippi river in the Township of Ramsay, County of Lanark. It was a station of the Brockville and Ottawa Railway.<ref>The province of Ontario gazetteer and directory. H. McEvoy Editor and Compiler, Toronto : Robertson & Cook, Publishers, 1869</ref> By the 1870 the town had thirty stores and forty other businesses.<ref>http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_5686_1.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403154215/http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_5686_1.html |date=2012-04-03 }} Ontario Heritage Trust Founding of Almonte</ref>\n\n===Origin of the name Almonte===\nDuring this time of rapid expansion the town changed its name from Shipman's Mills to Ramsayville, and then to Waterford.  When in 1855 the newly created Canadian post office pointed out there was already a Waterford in Ontario, the town needed yet another name change.<ref name=Frank>Cosentino, Frank. (2000).[https://books.google.com/books?id=BAOrZoCzYG8C&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=almonte+ramsayville+waterford&source=bl&ots=4_vCAX2cwM&sig=PuInmkD5oqRG7ZrMNJx7YJtKgyU&hl=en&ei=xEx4S9_AKaSb8Qa-yKn0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CCAQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=almonte%20ramsayville%20waterford&f=false ''Almonte: the life of Juan Nepomuceno Almonte''], pp.4-5, General Store Publishing.</ref>\n\nRelations between the [[United States]] and [[Great Britain]] had been antagonistic since the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] and later the [[War of 1812]]. Border wars between Mexico and the United States in the 1830s increased this antagonism.  Mexican general [[Juan Almonte]] had fought honourably in these latter wars, and by 1853 had become [[Mexico]]'s ambassador to the United States.\n\nIn the ensuing climate of Canadian mistrust of American territorial ambitions, General Almonte's name would have been well known to Waterford's citizens. Though there is no decisive evidence as to the final motive for the name change, it appears likely that Waterford saw Almonte as a \"principled David fighting a Goliath interested in swallowing up all North America.\"<ref name=Frank/>\n\nThe proposed name change was accepted by the Combined Counties of Lanark and Renfrew in June 1855, although the post office didn't record the new name until 1859.<ref name=Frank/> Whenever the name may have been formally accepted, it led to Almonte being the only community in Ontario, and likely Canada, to be named for a Mexican general.<ref name=\"Frank\" />\n\n=== Almonte train wreck, 1942 ===\n\nOn December 27, 1942, a troop train rear-ended a passenger train standing in the station at Almonte. Thirty-nine people were killed and more than 150 were injured.<ref>\"Troop special plows into local at Almonte\", ''Globe and Mail'', December 28, 1942, pg.1</ref> The local genealogy page<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sites.rootsweb.com/~onlanark/NewspaperClippings/Book2/NewspaperClippings13.htm|title=The Ottawa Journal|website=sites.rootsweb.com}}</ref> provides photos and a contemporary newspaper report of the wreck.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Former Almonte Post Office February 2012.jpg|The former Almonte Post Office\nFile:Train wreck - Almonte, Ontario, Canada (12-27-1942).jpg|Almonte train wreck, 1942\nFile:Naismith statue, Almonte.jpg|Sculpture of James Naismith\n</gallery>\n\n===Present day===\n[[File:Almonte Old Town Hall.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Town Hall in Almonte]]\nAfter the last [[textile mill]] closed in the early 1980s, Almonte no longer had a dominant industry.  It has since turned its attention towards [[tourism]].  It offers museums and several historical spots, such as the home of [[James Naismith]], the inventor of [[basketball]], and the Mississippi Valley Textile Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mvtm.ca/museum/|title=Mississippi Valley Textile Museum \u2013 museum}}</ref>\n\nAlmonte retains much of its 19th-century architecture. The former Almonte post office, designed in 1889 by [[Thomas Fuller (architect)|Thomas Fuller]] (the architect of the [[Parliament Buildings (Canada)|Parliament Buildings]]), and the Rosamond Woollen Mill, the largest 19th-century [[textile mill]] in Canada, are both designated as [[National Historic Sites of Canada]].<ref>{{CRHP|15041|Former Almonte Post Office}}</ref><ref>{{CRHP|7864|Rosamond Woollen Mill}}</ref>\n\nAlmonte has a skate park and splash pad which is open to the public and is located at the arena.\n\n==Events and attractions==\n\n===Festivals===\nAlmonte is home to several festivals and events, including the North Lanark Highland Games,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://almontehighlandgames.com/|title=North Lanark Highland Games &#124; Scottish culture and heritage of the Ottawa Valley}}</ref> Naismith 3-on-3 Basketball Festival,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051025085646/http://www.naismithmuseum.com/naismith_programsevents/main_3on3.htm|title=Naismith Museum And Hall Of Fame|date=October 25, 2005|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> Almonte Celtfest<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://almonteceltfest.com/|title=Almonte Celtfest \u2013 Ottawa Valley and Celtic entertainment}}</ref> and Busfusion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://busfusion.com/|title=BusFusion|website=busfusion.com}}</ref>\n\n====North Lanark Highland Games====\nThe  North Lanark Highland Games<ref name=\"auto1\"/> have been held annually in Almonte since 1982.\n\nThe [[Highland games|Games]] feature traditional Highland sports and entertainment, and bring in about 6,000 visitors each summer.\n\n====Almonte Celtfest====\n\nThe Almonte Celtfest<ref name=\"auto\"/> has been held annually in Almonte's Gemmill Park since 1997. The festival's goal is to \"celebrate and promote the Celtic heritage of the Ottawa Valley through music and dance.\"\n\n===Schools===\nAlmonte has three elementary schools:\n* R. Tait McKenzie Public School<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924041718/http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Elementary/RTM/homepage.htm|title=Welcome to UCDSB Portal|date=September 24, 2009|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n* Naismith Memorial Public School<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707064617/http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Elementary/NMS/homepage.htm|title=Welcome to UCDSB Portal|date=July 7, 2007|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n* Holy Name of Mary Catholic School<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdsbeo.on.ca/?school=holy-name-of-mary-catholic-school|title=Holy Name of Mary Catholic School \u2013 Catholic District School Board of Eastern Ontario \u2013 CDSBEO}}</ref>\n\n[[Almonte and District High School]] serves the town of Almonte and much of the surrounding rural area. The Almonte campus of the T.R. Leger School<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Continuing+Education/TRL/Campuses/Almonte/Almonte+Campus.htm|title=Almonte campus of the T.R. Leger School}}</ref> provides adult education and literacy classes.\n\n==Mississippi River==\nThe [[Mississippi River (Ontario)|Mississippi River]] which runs through Almonte has no connection with the U.S. river of the same name.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* {{official|http://almonte.com/ }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070404011132/http://almonte.com/images_hist/map_1863.jpg Town map, 1863 (JPEG)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Lanark County]]\n[[Category:Former towns in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Almonte\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Community <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = File:Almonte Ontario Canada.jpeg\n|imagesize              = 300px\n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Ontario<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Ontario\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 170\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Canada}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Ontario}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Lanark County, Ontario|Lanark]]\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =     \n|leader_name            = \n|leader_title1          =\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = 4.41\n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_water_percent       = \n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 4,752\n|population_density_km2         = 1077.4 \n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|45.22629|-76.19452|region:CA-ON_type:city(4649)|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n| postal_code_type      = Postal Code\n| postal_code           = K0A 1A0 & K0A 4A0\n|area_code              = [[Area code 613|613]]\n|blank_name             = [[Telephone exchange|256]]\n|blank_info             =  \n|footnotes              =  \n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n'''Almonte''' (pronounced \"AL-mont\" as opposed to the original Spanish pronunciation of \"al-MON-tay\")  is a former mill town located in [[Lanark County, Ontario|Lanark County]], in the eastern portion of Ontario, Canada. Formerly a separate municipality, Almonte is now a ward of the town of [[Mississippi Mills, Ontario|Mississippi Mills]], which was created on January 1, 1998, by the merging of Almonte with Ramsay and Pakenham townships.<ref>County of Lanark website  [http://www.county.lanark.on.ca/Page283.aspx ''Lanark County: Local Municipalities''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828095815/http://www.county.lanark.on.ca/Page283.aspx |date=2010-08-28 }}, last retrieved February 14, 2010</ref> Almonte is located {{convert|46|km|mi|0}} south-west of downtown [[Ottawa]]. Its population as of 2013 is about 5,000.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mississippi Mills Waterfalls.jpeg|thumb|right|Mississippi Mills Waterfalls]]\n\n===First settlers===\nAlmonte's first European-bred settler was David Shepherd, who in 1818 was given {{convert|200|acre|km2}} by the Crown to build and operate a [[Mill (grinding)|mill]].  The site became known as Shepherd's Falls.  That name was never official, however, and Shepherd sold his [[patent]] after his mill burned down.  The buyer of the patent, [[Daniel Shipman]], rebuilt the mill and the settlement became known as Shipman's Mills by about 1821.<ref>Wheatley, Gerry. [http://almonte.clal.ca/articles/almonte_early_history.htm \"David Shepherd was Almonte's first settler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223223039/http://almonte.clal.ca/articles/almonte_early_history.htm |date=2008-12-23 }}, ''The Almonte Gazette'', Almonte,  February 26, 1992</ref>\n\nThe majority of Shipman's Mills' early settlers were [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and later [[Irish people|Irish]].   A textile town almost from the start, by 1850 it was the home of seven busy woolen mills of Messrs B & W Rosamond. It was one of the leading centres in Ontario for the manufacture of woollen cloth. \nThe construction of a railway line to Brockville stimulated the economic growth of Almonte.\n\nIn 1869, Almonte was a village with a population of 2000 situated on the Mississippi river in the Township of Ramsay, County of Lanark. It was a station of the Brockville and Ottawa Railway.<ref>The province of Ontario gazetteer and directory. H. McEvoy Editor and Compiler, Toronto : Robertson & Cook, Publishers, 1869</ref> By the 1870 the town had thirty stores and forty other businesses.<ref>http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_5686_1.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403154215/http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_5686_1.html |date=2012-04-03 }} Ontario Heritage Trust Founding of Almonte</ref>\n\n===Origin of the name Almonte===\nDuring this time of rapid expansion the town changed its name from Shipman's Mills to Ramsayville, and then to Waterford.  When in 1855 the newly created Canadian post office pointed out there was already a Waterford in Ontario, the town needed yet another name change.<ref name=Frank>Cosentino, Frank. (2000).[https://books.google.com/books?id=BAOrZoCzYG8C&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=almonte+ramsayville+waterford&source=bl&ots=4_vCAX2cwM&sig=PuInmkD5oqRG7ZrMNJx7YJtKgyU&hl=en&ei=xEx4S9_AKaSb8Qa-yKn0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CCAQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=almonte%20ramsayville%20waterford&f=false ''Almonte: the life of Juan Nepomuceno Almonte''], pp.4-5, General Store Publishing.</ref>\n\nRelations between the [[United States]] and [[Great Britain]] had been antagonistic since the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] and later the [[War of 1812]]. Border wars between Mexico and the United States in the 1830s increased this antagonism.  Mexican general [[Juan Almonte]] had fought honourably in these latter wars, and by 1853 had become [[Mexico]]'s ambassador to the United States.\n\nIn the ensuing climate of Canadian mistrust of American territorial ambitions, General Almonte's name would have been well known to Waterford's citizens. Though there is no decisive evidence as to the final motive for the name change, it appears likely that Waterford saw Almonte as a \"principled David fighting a Goliath interested in swallowing up all North America.\"<ref name=Frank/>\n\nThe proposed name change was accepted by the Combined Counties of Lanark and Renfrew in June 1855, although the post office didn't record the new name until 1859.<ref name=Frank/> Whenever the name may have been formally accepted, it led to Almonte being the only community in Ontario, and likely Canada, to be named for a Mexican general.<ref name=\"Frank\" />\n\n=== Almonte train wreck, 1942 ===\n\nOn December 27, 1942, a troop train rear-ended a passenger train standing in the station at Almonte. Thirty-nine people were killed and more than 150 were injured.<ref>\"Troop special plows into local at Almonte\", ''Globe and Mail'', December 28, 1942, pg.1</ref> The local genealogy page<ref>http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~onlanark/NewspaperClippings/Book2/NewspaperClippings13.htm</ref> provides photos and a contemporary newspaper report of the wreck.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Former Almonte Post Office February 2012.jpg|The former Almonte Post Office\nFile:Train wreck - Almonte, Ontario, Canada (12-27-1942).jpg|Almonte train wreck, 1942\nFile:Naismith statue, Almonte.jpg|Sculpture of James Naismith\n</gallery>\n\n===Present day===\n[[File:Almonte Old Town Hall.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Town Hall in Almonte]]\nAfter the last [[textile mill]] closed in the early 1980s, Almonte no longer had a dominant industry.  It has since turned its attention towards [[tourism]].  It offers museums and several historical spots, such as the home of [[James Naismith]], the inventor of [[basketball]], and the Mississippi Valley Textile Museum.<ref>http://mvtm.ca/museum/</ref>\n\nAlmonte retains much of its 19th-century architecture. The former Almonte post office, designed in 1889 by [[Thomas Fuller (architect)|Thomas Fuller]] (the architect of the [[Parliament Buildings (Canada)|Parliament Buildings]]), and the Rosamond Woollen Mill, the largest 19th-century [[textile mill]] in Canada, are both designated as [[National Historic Sites of Canada]].<ref>{{CRHP|15041|Former Almonte Post Office}}</ref><ref>{{CRHP|7864|Rosamond Woollen Mill}}</ref>\n\nAlmonte has a skate park and splash pad which is open to the public and is located at the arena.\n\n==Events and attractions==\n\n===Festivals===\nAlmonte is home to several festivals and events, including the North Lanark Highland Games,<ref>http://www.almontehighlandgames.com/</ref> Naismith 3-on-3 Basketball Festival,<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20051025085646/http://www.naismithmuseum.com/naismith_programsevents/main_3on3.htm</ref> Almonte Celtfest<ref>http://almonteceltfest.com/</ref> and Busfusion.<ref>http://busfusion.com/</ref>\n\n====North Lanark Highland Games====\nThe  North Lanark Highland Games<ref>http://almontehighlandgames.com/</ref> have been held annually in Almonte since 1982.\n\nThe [[Highland games|Games]] feature traditional Highland sports and entertainment, and bring in about 6,000 visitors each summer.\n\n====Almonte Celtfest====\n\nThe Almonte Celtfest<ref>http://almonteceltfest.com/</ref> has been held annually in Almonte's Gemmill Park since 1997. The festival's goal is to \"celebrate and promote the Celtic heritage of the Ottawa Valley through music and dance.\"\n\n===Schools===\nAlmonte has three elementary schools:\n* R. Tait McKenzie Public School<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20090924041718/http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Elementary/RTM/homepage.htm</ref>\n* Naismith Memorial Public School<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20070707064617/http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Elementary/NMS/homepage.htm</ref>\n* Holy Name of Mary Catholic School<ref>http://www.cdsbeo.on.ca/?school=holy-name-of-mary-catholic-school</ref>\n\n[[Almonte and District High School]] serves the town of Almonte and much of the surrounding rural area. The Almonte campus of the T.R. Leger School<ref>[http://www.ucdsb.on.ca/Schools/School+Directory/Continuing+Education/TRL/Campuses/Almonte/Almonte+Campus.htm Almonte campus of the T.R. Leger School]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> provides adult education and literacy classes.\n\n==Mississippi River==\nThe [[Mississippi River (Ontario)|Mississippi River]] which runs through Almonte has no connection with the U.S. river of the same name.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* {{official|http://almonte.com/ }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070404011132/http://almonte.com/images_hist/map_1863.jpg Town map, 1863 (JPEG)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Lanark County]]\n[[Category:Former towns in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 1998]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 11 bare reference(s) wit